is excluded for and why.</p>\n\n<p>You should also be told how to challenge the exclusion, if you want to. </p>\n\n<p>Exclusions can start the same day but the school can&rsquo;t make you collect your child straight away.</p>\n\n<h3>Risk of prosecution if child is found in public place</h3>\n\n<p>For the first 5 school days of an exclusion, it&rsquo;s your responsibility to make sure your child isn&rsquo;t in a public place during normal school hours unless there is a good reason.</p>\n\n<p>If your child is found in a public place when they&rsquo;re not supposed to be, <a href=\"/school-attendance-absence\" title=\"School attendance and absence\">you might be prosecuted</a>.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice help-notice\">\n<p>You can get <a href=\"/school-discipline-exclusions/help-and-advice\" title=\"Get free legal advice\">get free legal advice</a> if your child has been excluded.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Types of exclusion</h2>\n\n<p>There are 2 kinds of exclusion - fixed period (suspended) and permanent (expelled).</p>\n\n<h3>Fixed period exclusion</h3>\n\n<p>A fixed period exclusion is where your child is temporarily removed from school. They can only be removed for up to 45 school days in 1 school year. </p>\n\n<p>If a child has been excluded for a fixed period, schools should set and mark work for the first 5 school days.</p>\n\n<p>If the exclusion is longer than 5 school days, the school must arrange full-time education from the 6th school day.</p>\n\n<h3>Permanent exclusion</h3>\n\n<p>Permanent exclusion means your child is expelled. The local council must arrange full-time education from the 6th school day. </p>\n\n<h3>Alternative education and exclusion</h3>\n\n<p>The school must tell you about any arrangements that have been made for your child to attend alternative education. If alternative education is arranged then it&rsquo;s your responsibility to make sure your child attends.</p>\n\n<h2>Challenging exclusion</h2>\n\n<p>The letter from school about the exclusion will tell you how to challenge the decision. </p>\n\n<h3>Challenging fixed period exclusion</h3>\n\n<p>You can challenge fixed period exclusions if a pupil has been excluded for more than 5 school days in a term or an exclusion will mean they will miss a public exam or national curriculum test. For exclusions of 5 school days or less, parents can ask the governing body to consider their views.</p>\n\n<h3>Challenging permanent exclusion</h3>\n\n<p>You can challenge permanent exclusion with the governing body. If they agree with the exclusion, you can appeal to the local council or the Academy Trust if the school is an <a href=\"/types-of-school/academies\" title=\"Academies\">academy</a>. The governing body must tell you how to do this.</p>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/school-discipline-exclusions/searches","slug":"searches","order":3,"title":"Searches","body":"<h2>Searches without your child&rsquo;s consent</h2>\n\n<p>The school doesn&rsquo;t need your child&rsquo;s consent to search them if they think your child has prohibited items:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>weapons, eg knives</li>\n  <li>alcohol</li>\n  <li>illegal drugs</li>\n  <li>stolen goods</li>\n  <li>tobacco products, eg cigarettes</li>\n  <li>pornographic images (of any kind, eg tabloid topless pictures and &lsquo;lads&rsquo; mags&rsquo; as well as extreme adult material)</li>\n  <li>fireworks</li>\n  <li>anything that has been, or is likely to be, used to cause injury or commit an offence</li>\n  <li>anything banned in the school rules</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>These things can be confiscated. </p>\n\n<h2>Legal requirements of a search</h2>\n\n<p>There should normally be 2 members of staff present during the search - the person doing the search and the search witness. Searches should normally be done by someone the same sex as your child.</p>\n\n<p>The search witness must also be the same sex as your child if possible. Your child must not be asked to remove clothes, other than outer clothing like a coat.</p>\n\n<p>If there&rsquo;s a risk of serious harm to a person if the search is not conducted immediately, a child may be searched by a person of the opposite sex and without another member of staff present.</p>\n\n<h2>Metal detectors</h2>\n\n<p>Schools can make pupils go through a metal detector - they don&rsquo;t have to suspect that your child has a weapon. If your child refuses to go through the metal detector, they can be stopped from coming into school.</p>\n\n<h2>Complaining about a search</h2>\n\n<p>If you&rsquo;re unhappy with a search on your child at school, talk to the headteacher. If you&rsquo;re not satisfied, ask for a copy of the complaints procedure.</p>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/school-discipline-exclusions/help-and-advice","slug":"help-and-advice","order":4,"title":"Help and advice","body":"<p>You can get free legal advice and information on children&rsquo;s schooling and education rights from the Coram Children&rsquo;s Legal Centre.</p>\n\n<p>You can download factsheets from the website or talk to an advisor online or on the phone.</p>\n\n<div class=\"contact\">\n<p><strong>Coram Childrenâs Legal Centre</strong></p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://t2.phplivesupport.com/cclcuk/phplive.php?d=0&amp;btn=1349626075&amp;onpage=hphp%3A%2F%2Fwww.childrenslegalcentre.com%2Findex.php%3Fpage%3Dweb_chat&amp;title=Coram%20Children's%20Legal%20Centre%20web%20chat&amp;theme=&amp;js_name=&amp;js_email=&amp;widget=0&amp;custom=&amp;theme=&amp;js_name=&amp;js_email=&amp;widget=0&amp;custom=&amp;theme=&amp;js_name=&amp;js_email=&amp;widget=0&amp;custom=\" title=\"chat online\">Chat online with an advisor</a>    <br />\nMonday to Friday, 9am to 6pm  </p>\n\n<p><strong>Telephone:</strong> 08088 020 008  <br />\nMonday to Friday, 8am to 8pm<br />\n<a href=\"http://www.childrenslegalcentre.com/index.php?page=schools_and_education\" title=\"Coram Childrenâs Legal Centre\">www.childrenslegalcentre.com</a></p>\n</div>\n\n"}]},"tags":[{"title":"School life","id":"